-- MATHEMATICS Paper 2
INSERT INTO questions (subject, paper_number, question_type, section, topic, year, question_text, options, correct_answer_index, explanation, difficulty, marks, mark_scheme) VALUES

('Mathematics',2,'structured','A','Algebra',2022,
'(a) Factorise completely: 6x² + 7x − 3. (b) Hence or otherwise, solve 6x² + 7x − 3 = 0. (c) Using your answer to (b), find the values of x if 6(2y+1)² + 7(2y+1) − 3 = 0.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',12,
'(a) (3x−1)(2x+3) [4 marks: 2 for each factor]. (b) x = 1/3 or x = −3/2 [2 marks]. (c) Substitute 2y+1 = 1/3 → y = −1/3; 2y+1 = −3/2 → y = −5/4 [6 marks: method 2, each value 2]'),

('Mathematics',2,'structured','A','Mensuration',2021,
'The diagram shows a cylindrical tank of radius 1.4 m and height 3 m. (a) Calculate the volume of the tank in m³ (π = 22/7). (b) Water fills the tank to 80% of its capacity. Find the volume of water in litres. (c) If water is pumped out at 0.5 m³ per minute, how long will it take to empty the water?',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',12,
'(a) V = πr²h = (22/7)(1.4²)(3) = (22/7)(1.96)(3) = 18.48 m³ [4 marks]. (b) 80% of 18.48 = 14.784 m³ = 14,784 litres [4 marks: conversion 1, multiplication 3]. (c) Time = 14.784 ÷ 0.5 = 29.568 ≈ 29.6 minutes [4 marks]'),

('Mathematics',2,'essay','B','Statistics',2022,
'The ages (in years) of 30 students in a class are given: 15, 16, 15, 17, 16, 15, 18, 16, 17, 15, 16, 17, 15, 18, 16, 17, 15, 16, 17, 18, 15, 16, 17, 15, 16, 17, 18, 16, 15, 17. (a) Construct a frequency table for the data. (b) Calculate the mean age. (c) Find the modal age. (d) Draw a frequency polygon for the data.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',20,
'(a) Frequency table: 15→8, 16→9, 17→8, 18→5 [5 marks: table heading 1, 4 correct rows 4]. (b) Mean = (15×8+16×9+17×8+18×5)/30 = (120+144+136+90)/30 = 490/30 = 16.33 years [6 marks]. (c) Mode = 16 (highest frequency) [3 marks]. (d) Frequency polygon: correct axes 2, correct points plotted 4, lines joined 2, labels 2 [6 marks]'),

('Mathematics',2,'essay','B','Trigonometry',2021,
'(a) In triangle PQR, PQ = 8 cm, QR = 6 cm and angle PQR = 90°. (i) Find PR. (ii) Find angle QPR to the nearest degree. (b) A ladder of length 5 m leans against a vertical wall. The foot of the ladder is 3 m from the base of the wall. Calculate: (i) the height the ladder reaches up the wall; (ii) the angle the ladder makes with the ground.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',20,
'(a)(i) PR = √(8²+6²) = √(64+36) = √100 = 10 cm [4 marks]. (a)(ii) tan(QPR) = 6/8 = 0.75 → angle QPR = 36.87° ≈ 37° [4 marks]. (b)(i) h = √(5²−3²) = √(25−9) = √16 = 4 m [4 marks]. (b)(ii) cosθ = 3/5 = 0.6 → θ = 53.13° ≈ 53° [4 marks: formula 1, substitution 1, answer 2]. Award process marks throughout [4 marks]');

-- BIOLOGY Paper 2
INSERT INTO questions (subject, paper_number, question_type, section, topic, year, question_text, options, correct_answer_index, explanation, difficulty, marks, mark_scheme) VALUES

('Biology',2,'structured','A','Nutrition',2022,
'(a) Name FOUR classes of food and give ONE example of a food source for each. (b) State THREE functions of proteins in the human body. (c) What is the role of bile in digestion?',
'[]',0,'',
'easy',15,
'(a) Any 4 of: Carbohydrates (e.g. rice/bread), Proteins (e.g. meat/beans), Fats/Lipids (e.g. oil/butter), Vitamins (e.g. fruits/vegetables), Minerals (e.g. milk/leafy greens), Water. [1 mark per class + example = 8 marks, max 4×2=8]. (b) Any 3 of: Growth and repair of tissues; Production of enzymes and hormones; Defence (antibodies); Energy source (last resort) [1 mark each]. (c) Bile emulsifies fats into small droplets, increasing surface area for lipase to act on them [2 marks].'),

('Biology',2,'structured','A','Human Biology',2021,
'(a) Name the chambers of the human heart and state their functions. (b) Distinguish between arteries and veins. (c) What is the role of haemoglobin in the blood?',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',12,
'(a) 4 chambers: Right atrium (receives deoxygenated blood from body), Right ventricle (pumps to lungs), Left atrium (receives oxygenated blood from lungs), Left ventricle (pumps oxygenated blood to body). [1 mark per chamber name, 1 mark per correct function = 8 marks]. (b) Arteries: carry blood away from heart, thick muscular walls, high pressure, no valves (except aortic valve). Veins: carry blood to heart, thinner walls, lower pressure, have valves to prevent backflow [2 marks each, max 4]. (c) Haemoglobin binds to oxygen in the lungs to form oxyhaemoglobin and releases oxygen to body tissues [2 marks].'),

('Biology',2,'essay','B','Ecology',2022,
'(a) Define the following ecological terms: (i) ecosystem; (ii) food chain; (iii) niche. (b) Construct a food chain with FOUR trophic levels using organisms found in a tropical forest. Label each trophic level. (c) Explain how energy is lost at each trophic level and why this limits the length of food chains.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',20,
'(a)(i) An ecosystem is a community of living organisms interacting with each other and their non-living (abiotic) environment [2 marks]. (a)(ii) A food chain shows the sequence in which energy passes from one organism to another through feeding relationships [2 marks]. (a)(iii) The niche is the role or function of an organism in its ecosystem — where it lives and what it eats [2 marks]. (b) e.g. Leaves → Caterpillar → Bird → Eagle; each level correctly labelled as producer/primary consumer/secondary consumer/tertiary consumer [4 marks]. (c) Only 10% of energy passes to next trophic level; 90% lost as heat, movement, and waste. This means energy becomes insufficient to support organisms beyond 4-5 levels [6 marks]. Quality of explanation [4 marks]');

-- CHEMISTRY Paper 2
INSERT INTO questions (subject, paper_number, question_type, section, topic, year, question_text, options, correct_answer_index, explanation, difficulty, marks, mark_scheme) VALUES

('Chemistry',2,'structured','A','Moles and Calculations',2022,
'(a) Define the term "mole". (b) Calculate the number of moles in 18 g of water (H=1, O=16). (c) A solution contains 5.85 g of sodium chloride (NaCl) dissolved in 500 cm³ of water. Calculate its concentration in mol/dm³ (Na=23, Cl=35.5).',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',12,
'(a) The mole is the amount of substance containing 6.02×10²³ (Avogadro''s number) particles [2 marks]. (b) Molar mass of H₂O = 2(1)+16 = 18 g/mol. Moles = 18/18 = 1 mol [3 marks]. (c) Molar mass NaCl = 23+35.5 = 58.5 g/mol. Moles = 5.85/58.5 = 0.1 mol. Volume = 500/1000 = 0.5 dm³. Concentration = 0.1/0.5 = 0.2 mol/dm³ [7 marks: MM 2, moles 2, conversion 1, concentration 2].'),

('Chemistry',2,'essay','B','Electrochemistry',2021,
'(a) Define electrolysis. (b) During the electrolysis of dilute sulphuric acid using platinum electrodes: (i) name the product at each electrode; (ii) write the half-equations for each electrode reaction; (iii) explain why twice the volume of gas is collected at the cathode compared to the anode. (c) State TWO industrial applications of electrolysis.',
'[]',0,'',
'hard',20,
'(a) Electrolysis is the decomposition of an ionic compound in molten or aqueous form using electricity [2 marks]. (b)(i) Cathode: hydrogen gas. Anode: oxygen gas [2 marks]. (b)(ii) Cathode: 2H⁺ + 2e⁻ → H₂. Anode: 4OH⁻ → 2H₂O + O₂ + 4e⁻ [4 marks: 2 each]. (b)(iii) For every mole of O₂ produced (4 electrons), 2 moles of H₂ are produced (4 electrons). H₂:O₂ = 2:1 by volume [4 marks]. (c) Any 2: electroplating, extraction of aluminium, purification of copper, chlorine/NaOH production [2 marks each = 4 marks]. Quality [4 marks].'),

-- PHYSICS Paper 2
('Physics',2,'structured','A','Mechanics',2022,
'A car of mass 1200 kg accelerates uniformly from rest to 20 m/s in 8 seconds. (a) Calculate the acceleration of the car. (b) Calculate the force required to produce this acceleration. (c) Calculate the kinetic energy of the car at 20 m/s. (d) If the car then brakes to a stop in 5 seconds, calculate the braking force.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',12,
'(a) a = (v-u)/t = (20-0)/8 = 2.5 m/s² [3 marks: formula 1, substitution 1, answer 1]. (b) F = ma = 1200 × 2.5 = 3000 N [3 marks]. (c) KE = ½mv² = ½ × 1200 × 400 = 240,000 J = 240 kJ [3 marks]. (d) a = (0-20)/5 = -4 m/s². F = 1200 × 4 = 4800 N [3 marks]. Award full marks only where formula, substitution, working, and unit are shown.'),

('Physics',2,'essay','B','Electricity',2021,
'(a) State Ohm''s Law. (b) In the circuit, three resistors of 4Ω, 6Ω, and 12Ω are connected in parallel across a 12 V battery. (i) Calculate the total resistance. (ii) Calculate the total current drawn from the battery. (iii) Calculate the current through the 6Ω resistor. (c) Calculate the power dissipated in the 12Ω resistor. (d) Explain why household appliances are connected in parallel rather than series.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',20,
'(a) Ohm''s Law: the current through a conductor is directly proportional to the potential difference across it, provided temperature remains constant [2 marks]. (b)(i) 1/R = 1/4+1/6+1/12 = 3/12+2/12+1/12 = 6/12 = 1/2. R = 2Ω [4 marks]. (b)(ii) I = V/R = 12/2 = 6 A [3 marks]. (b)(iii) I₆ = V/R₆ = 12/6 = 2 A [3 marks]. (c) P = V²/R = 144/12 = 12 W (or I=1A, P=I²R=12W) [3 marks]. (d) In parallel: each appliance gets full voltage; one failing doesn''t affect others; each can be switched independently [3 marks]. Process marks: formula, substitution, unit [2 marks].'),

-- ECONOMICS Paper 2
('Economics',2,'essay','A','Supply and Demand',2022,
'(a) With the aid of a diagram, explain the law of demand. (b) State FOUR non-price factors that can cause the demand curve to shift. (c) Using a demand and supply diagram, explain what happens to the equilibrium price and quantity of petrol when (i) its price rises sharply; (ii) a new refinery opens in Liberia.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',20,
'(a) Law of demand: as price rises, quantity demanded falls (inverse relationship), ceteris paribus. Diagram: correctly labelled downward-sloping demand curve with P on y-axis, Q on x-axis [6 marks: explanation 3, diagram 3]. (b) Any 4: changes in income, prices of substitutes/complements, consumer tastes/preferences, advertising, population size, future price expectations [1 mark each = 4 marks]. (c)(i) Price rise: move along demand curve (contraction in demand), quantity demanded falls [3 marks]. (c)(ii) New refinery increases supply, supply shifts right, equilibrium price falls, equilibrium quantity rises [5 marks: supply shift 2, price 1.5, quantity 1.5]. Quality of diagrams [2 marks].'),

-- GEOGRAPHY Paper 2
('Geography',2,'essay','A','Physical Geography',2022,
'(a) Describe the formation of a waterfall. (b) With the aid of a diagram, explain how a meander is formed and how it eventually becomes an oxbow lake. (c) Explain THREE ways in which rivers are useful to people in West Africa.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',20,
'(a) Waterfall: forms where hard resistant rock overlies softer rock. Soft rock erodes faster by abrasion and hydraulic action; hard rock is undercut and eventually collapses; a plunge pool forms at the base [6 marks: process 4, location/outcome 2]. (b) Meander: maximum velocity on outer bank causes erosion (undercutting), while inner bank deposits material (point bar). Over time loop becomes tighter. During flood, river cuts through the neck, abandoning the loop as an oxbow lake [8 marks: diagram 3, formation 3, oxbow 2]. (c) Any 3: irrigation for agriculture, hydroelectric power generation, water supply for drinking, fishing, transport, tourism [2 marks each = 6 marks].'),

-- ENGLISH LANGUAGE Paper 2
('English Language',2,'essay','A','Essay Writing',2022,
'Write a well-organised essay of about 450 words on ONE of the following topics: (A) "Technology has done more harm than good." Discuss. OR (B) Write a letter to the Minister of Education in Liberia arguing for free secondary school education for all students. OR (C) Tell the story of a day when everything went wrong.',
'[]',0,'',
'medium',40,
'Marking criteria: Content/Relevance 15, Organisation/Structure 10, Language Use/Grammar 10, Vocabulary 5. A: Must present BOTH sides of argument before concluding. B: Must follow formal letter format (address, date, salutation, body paragraphs, closing). C: Must tell a clear story with beginning, middle, end. Deduct marks for: topic not addressed 0-10, poor organisation 0-5, repetition/irrelevance 0-5.'),

-- LITERATURE Paper 2
('Literature in English',2,'essay','A','African Prose',2022,
'Answer ONE of the following questions on the African prose text you have studied: (A) Examine the role of women in the novel. How does the author''s presentation of female characters contribute to the themes of the work? OR (B) Discuss how the theme of conflict (between tradition and modernity, or between individuals) is developed in the novel. Use specific examples from the text to support your answer.',
'[]',0,'',
'hard',25,
'Marking criteria: Knowledge of text 8, Analysis of theme/character 8, Use of textual evidence 5, Expression and organisation 4. Students must: identify specific characters/events, analyse rather than merely summarise, use quotations or close reference, maintain a clear argument throughout. Deduct heavily for plot retelling without analysis [0-8 marks for mere summary].');

